 "373-423K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "clay interface and wet-dry concentration", "aqueous": false, "other": "Alkaline conditions near pH 9.8 favor dimerization during dry phase"}, "mechanism": "Dehydrative peptide bond formation between two glycine molecules yields glycylglycine under cyclical concentration and heating.", "reasoning": "Glycine oligomerization is promoted during wet-dry cycling, especially under alkaline conditions near pH 9.8, and clay minerals strongly enhance peptide formation; this reaction captures the first biochemical use of glycine after its synthesis (Rode et al., 1999; Lambert, Gurusamy-Thangavelu & Ma, 2010; Forsythe et al., 2015)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical cyclization of glycylglycine to diketopiperazine", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["null"], "conditions": {"temperature": "423K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thermal cyclization on drying mineral interface", "aqueous": false, "other": "Observed prominently in glycine oligomerization on montmorillonite during dry heating"}, "mechanism": "Intramolecular condensation of the dipeptide yields the cyclic dimer diketopiperazine.", "reasoning": "Montmorillonite-catalyzed dry-heating experiments show glycine conversion to cyclic dimers and short peptides, with diketopiperazine a characteristic product of glycine condensation networks (Bujdak et al., 1996; Lambert, Gurusamy-Thangavelu & Ma, 2010)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Hydrothermal glycolate-glyoxylate oxidation to glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite", "magnetite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-S/iron oxide redox mineral assemblage", "aqueous": true, "other": "Anoxic vent redox cycling"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-hydroxy acid oxidation on iron mineral surfaces converts glycolate into the corresponding alpha-keto acid glyoxylate.", "reasoning": "Iron-sulfur minerals catalyze redox interconversion between alpha-hydroxy acids and alpha-keto acids; thus glycolate provides a bridge from the oxyglycolate pathway back into the documented hydrothermal glyoxylate-to-glycine route (Muchowska et al., 2019; Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Surface HCN reservoir accumulation", "inputs": ["mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2", "sulfide minerals"], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "photochemical weathering of refractory organics", "aqueous": true, "other": "Speculative network-connecting degradation under UV-exposed pond margins"}, "mechanism": "Partial degradation/weathering of refractory nitrogenous organics releases simple nitrile feedstocks including cyanide equivalents back into surface chemistry.", "reasoning": "This step is explicitly speculative and added only to connect the Garakuta precursor reservoir to the better-established HCN-centered surface network. The report emphasizes unresolved transitions between complex organic reservoirs and discrete monomer chemistry, so this reaction addresses that gap while acknowledging uncertainty (Kobayashi et al., 1998; Takano et al., 2004; open-questions discussion in the provided report)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Classical surface Strecker pathway", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced C1 feedstock enters surface Strecker chemistry through formaldehyde, passing via methanimine and aminoacetonitrile to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal glyoxylate reductive amination with ammonia", "description": "Vent-generated glyoxylate is directly aminated on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces to glycine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_009"]}, {"path