such as ~100 C and mineral-specific setups\",\n        \"Differentiate ammonia-fed and nitrate-fed yields in the pathway discussion\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.7,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"The oxyglycolate route is a strong inclusion and matches recent literature qualitatively: glycolonitrile to hydroxyacetamide to glycolic acid/glycolate. The major issue is the final conversion of glycolate to glycine, which is presented as a direct SN2 amination; this is the least established part experimentally and is more computationally motivated than empirically validated. The pathway is coherent but not yet robust enough for approval.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify that the glycolate-to-glycine step is speculative/computationally proposed rather than strongly demonstrated\",\n        \"Add pH 8-9 basic-ocean context explicitly for the favorable oxyglycolate steps\",\n        \"Include mineral or ionic context for cyanide addition and hydrolysis steps\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.7,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.84,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid oxyglycolate-to-glyoxylate crossover is one of the more compelling network designs because it connects a surface cyanide chemistry branch to a hydrothermal iron-mineral amino acid synthesis branch. The glycolate-to-glyoxylate oxidation is plausible in the context of hydroxy acid/keto acid redox interconversion on iron minerals, and glyoxylate amination is literature-supported. Some upstream hydrothermal C1 chemistry remains weak, but this pathway itself is well integrated and environmentally realistic.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Explicitly tie rxn_018 to iron-sulfur or magnetite-mediated alpha-hydroxy acid/alpha-keto acid interconversion\",\n        \"Specify mineral catalysts for each surface step\",\n        \"Document transfer mechanism from surface pools to hydrothermal or interfacial settings\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"The cyanosulfidic photoredox route is well aligned with Sutherland-style systems chemistry: HCN, H2S, UV, and aqueous conditions producing aminonitriles, followed by hydrolysis to glycine. This pathway is concise and chemically plausible. It would be stronger with explicit mention of phosphate buffering and Cu photoredox context from the literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Add phosphate as a buffer/catalytic medium and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox context if intended\",\n        \"Clarify whether aminoacetonitrile is formed directly or through intermediate cyanohydrin/imine chemistry\",\n        \"Provide stronger conditions for the hydrolysis step\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.89,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.93,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.89,\n      \"feedback\": \"The Garakuta/CGP pathway aligns strongly with the literature summary. High-energy irradiation producing complex glycine precursors followed by hydrolysis to release glycine is well supported conceptually. The main limitation is that CGP is represented as a single abstract node, which simplifies a heterogeneous macromolecular reservoir. Nonetheless, this is a good literature-grounded route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Note that CGP is a heterogeneous macromolecular precursor ensemble rather than a discrete compound\",\n        \"Specify proton irradiation or solar energetic particle context more directly\",\n        \"Clarify hydrolysis conditions used to liberate glycine from CGP\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.91,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.25,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.63,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.58,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.68,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.61,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway is weakened by the step converting CGP into an HCN reservoir. The literature supports CGP as a macromolecular amino acid precursor, but not as a clean source of HCN for a downstream Strecker route. The rest of the pathway is acceptable once HCN is available, but the internal logic linking Garakuta chemistry to cyanide recycling is not well grounded.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_019\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Remove or heavily qualify the CGP-to-HCN conversion as speculative\",\n        \"If keeping it, provide a decomposition rationale and explicit energy source\",\n        \"Use direct CGP hydrolysis to glycine rather than rerouting through HCN\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.7,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.55\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.77,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.8,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"This branch is essentially another framing of the oxyglycolate route and shares its strengths and weaknesses. The pathway is chemically reasonable up to glycolate, but the terminal amination remains the least secure step. It is a useful alternative route but not fully validated experimentally.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_012\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Frame the last step as a proposed pathway rather than a settled reaction\",\n        \"Add supporting basic-ocean pH context and possible catalytic ions or minerals\",\n        \"Consider routing glycolate through glyoxylate before amination to strengthen plausibility\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.42,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.35,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.74,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.81,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.67,\n      \"feedback\": \"The cross-environment logic is good, but this hybrid route inherits the weakest hydrothermal reactions in the network. The downstream hydrothermal glyoxylate amination is plausible; the issue is still the unsupported formation of formaldehyde and glyoxylate from CO2 in the specific forms presented. Better hydrothermal feedstock chemistry would substantially improve this route.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Replace the initial hydrothermal carbon-fixation sequence with literature-backed formate/CO/acetyl intermediates\",\n        \"Use iron-sulfur or magnetite-catalyzed redox interconversion from glycolate to glyoxylate as the main hydrothermal entry\",\n        \"Provide explicit mineral assignments and vent conditions\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-connected and conceptually strong synthesis network with substantial environmental redundancy and multiple legitimate literature-inspired routes to glycine. Topologically, the network is good: it has sufficient node count, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and no obvious isolated subgraph. The best-supported branches are the classical Strecker pathway, the cyanosulfidic aminonitrile pathway, the Garakuta/CGP hydrolysis route, and the hybrid oxyglycolate-to-glyoxylate crossover. The principal weaknesses are chemical precision and literature fidelity in several reactions. In particular, mol_006 is misassigned as CH3NO instead of methanimine CH2NH; hydroxyacetamide is given the glycine formula instead of C2H5NO2? Actually hydroxyacetamide should not duplicate glycine identity in a network; and some hydrothermal reactions, especially direct CO2 + H2 to formaldehyde and formaldehyde + CO2 to glyoxylate, are insufficiently supported. The glycolate-to-glycine SN2 step is plausible only as a recent computational proposal, not a well-established prebiotic transformation. Environmental interconnection is a major strength, but the network fails a strict specification check because hydrothermal and surface reactions are described without explicit mineral agents, despite the original synthesis requirements. Literature alignment is moderate to good overall: the network captures the major known glycine routes from Strecker, cyanosulfidic chemistry, hydrothermal glyoxylate amination, nitrate/ferroan brucite chemistry, oxyglycolate proposals, and CGP hydrolysis, but some individual steps are overextended beyond current evidence.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.87,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.9\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.92, "rxn_007": 0.83}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.88, "pathway_coherence": 0.93, "environmental_progression": 0.89, "target_achievement": 0.92, "overall_confidence": 0.9, "feedback": "Classical Strecker route is the strongest pathway in the network and aligns well with literature: formaldehyde + ammonia to methanimine, cyanation to aminoacetonitrile, then hydrolysis to glycine. The main weakness is that aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis is the kinetic bottleneck and typically needs stronger aqueous or prolonged hydrothermal conditions than are stated. Still, this is a coherent, literature-supported route to glycine.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Specify explicit aqueous hydrolysis conditions for aminoacetonitrile, including prolonged wet conditions or elevated temperature", "Include mineral agents for the surface steps to satisfy the original network specification more rigorously", "Represent methanimine formula as CH2NH rather than CH3NO"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.42, "rxn_002": 0.35, "rxn_003": 0.78}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.52, "pathway_coherence": 0.68, "environmental_progression": 0.79, "target_achievement": 0.8, "overall_confidence": 0.64, "feedback": "The endpoint reaction, reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine under hydrothermal 