emical_feasibility": 0.85, "pathway_coherence": 0.88, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.87, "feedback": "The cyanosulfidic photoredox route is well aligned with Sutherland-style systems chemistry: HCN, H2S, UV, and aqueous conditions producing aminonitriles, followed by hydrolysis to glycine. This pathway is concise and chemically plausible. It would be stronger with explicit mention of phosphate buffering and Cu photoredox context from the literature.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Add phosphate as a buffer/catalytic medium and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox context if intended", "Clarify whether aminoacetonitrile is formed directly or through intermediate cyanohydrin/imine chemistry", "Provide stronger conditions for the hydrolysis step"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_014": 0.91, "rxn_015": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.89, "pathway_coherence": 0.87, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.93, "overall_confidence": 0.89, "feedback": "The Garakuta/CGP pathway aligns strongly with the literature summary. High-energy irradiation producing complex glycine precursors followed by hydrolysis to release glycine is well supported conceptually. The main limitation is that CGP is represented as a single abstract node, which simplifies a heterogeneous macromolecular reservoir. Nonetheless, this is a good literature-grounded route.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Note that CGP is a heterogeneous macromolecular precursor ensemble rather than a discrete compound", "Specify proton irradiation or solar energetic particle context more directly", "Clarify hydrolysis conditions used to liberate glycine from CGP"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_014": 0.91, "rxn_019": 0.25, "rxn_005": 0.9, "rxn_006": 0.92, "rxn_007": 0.83}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.63, "pathway_coherence": 0.58, "environmental_progression": 0.68, "ta