\"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H3O3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h3H,1H2,(H,4,5)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"NO3-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"nitrate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"nitrate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/NO3/c2-1(3)4/q-1\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethanedial\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxal\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminoacetamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycinamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H6N2O/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H2,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-[(2-aminoacetyl)amino]acetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycylglycine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O3/c5-1-3(7)6-2-4(8)9/h1-2,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"piperazine-2,5-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"diketopiperazine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6N2O2/c7-3-1-5-4(8)2-6-3/h1-2H2,(H,5,7)(H,6,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H5NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"complex glycine precursor hydrolysate equivalent\",\n      \"common_name\": \"CGP-derived glycine fraction\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type generation of formaldehyde from CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"serpentinization-linked reducing conditions; aldehyde-generating FTT chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface CO2 hydrogenation and partial reduction to C1 oxygenates on magnetite/Fe0 under hydrothermal reducing conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Supported at the network level by hydrothermal FTT chemistry on magnetite as a source of reduced carbon compounds and aldehydes in serpentinization settings; used here conservatively to supply formaldehyde as a shared feedstock rather than as a direct glycine route (Cody et al., 2000; McCollom, 2013). This addresses prior overextension by not forcing unsupported direct CO2-to-glyoxylate chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface photochemical production of HCN from formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation; anoxic surface setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-driven decomposition and rearrangement of formamide on photocatalytic mineral surfaces to HCN-bearing products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report identifies UV photochemistry of HCN plus water leading through formamide and nucleobase precursor chemistry; the reverse linkage as a source of HCN in prebiotic photochemical networks is widely discussed in formamide chemistry. Included to connect literature-described formamide/HCN photochemistry without inventing new glycine chemistry (Saladino et al., 2012; Ferus et al., 2015).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal iron-sulfur oxidation of glycolate to glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"anoxic vent interface; alpha-hydroxy/alpha-keto redox interconversion\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated oxidoreductive interconversion of alpha-hydroxy acid to alpha-keto acid on Fe-S surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically notes iron-sulfur minerals and pyrrhotite-like systems catalyzing glycolate/glyoxylate interconversion, making glyoxylate a plausible hydrothermal hub fed from surface hydroxy-acid chemistry. FeS/FeS2 are used here as the required hydrothermal mineral analogs (Keller et al., 2014; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal formation of glyoxylate from glyoxal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent to subseafloor redox conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydration/oxidation-state adjustment of dialdehyde feedstock on Fe-S mineral surfaces to alpha-keto acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxal and glyoxylate are closely linked C2 carbonyl pools in prebiotic carbonyl chemistry; this hydrothermal connector is more restrained than the previously criticized direct formaldehyde-plus-CO2 to glyoxylate shortcut. Included as a necessary connecting step consistent with Fe-S-mediated carbonyl transformations, though more speculative than the terminal glyoxylate amination (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN-formaldehyde addition to glycolonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, sulfide minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"basic to neutral aqueous ponds; cyanide addition to formaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic cyanide addition to formaldehyde generates cyanohydrin glycolonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The oxyglycolate path in the report begins explicitly with formation of glycolonitrile from formaldehyde and cyanide; this is one of the best-defined entry points to the non-Strecker glycine pathway (2024 computational oxyglycolate study cited in the report). Borate is included because it stabilizes small oxygenated carbonyl compounds in surface settings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydration-hydrolysis of glycolonitrile to hydroxyacetamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"basic pH approximately 8-9; hydration-hydrolysis sequence\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanohydrin nitrile hydration followed by amide formation through water-mediated proton transfers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step follows the newly proposed oxyglycolate pathway summarized in the report, where glycolonitrile undergoes hydration-hydrolysis to hydroxyacetamide and is favored under basic-ocean conditions. This is retained because it is literature-provided rather than invented (2024 computational oxyglycolate study in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydroxyacetamide conversion to glycolic acid/glycolate pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"basic pH approximately 8-9; hydrolysis and deprotonation in primitive ocean/pool conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Further hydration and hydrolysis convert the amide to glycolic acid, which partitions to glycolate under basic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies hydroxyacetamide to glycolic acid and then glycolate as the thermochemical sink of the oxyglycolate route in basic environments. Both acid and conjugate-base forms are output to respect pH-dependent speciation (2024 computational oxyglycolate study in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker condensation to methanimine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, phosphate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"aqueous condensation; neutral to mildly basic conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde condenses with ammonia to give methanimine via dehydration/iminium formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report explicitly states that classical Strecker synthesis proceeds through methanimine from formaldehyde, ammonia, and then HCN. This corrects the earlier chemical precision issue by using methanimine with the proper formula CH2NH (Woon, 2002; Elsila et al., 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker addition of HCN to methanimine forming aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"moist conditions; water-mediated proton relay lowers barrier substantially\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN adds to methanimine to form aminonitrile through proton-relay-assisted C-C bond formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core Strecker step. The report notes that with explicit water molecules the barrier drops dramatically and aminoacetonitrile formation becomes highly favorable in moist surroundings and on icy analog surfaces. Here it is mapped to surface aqueous prebiotic chemistry as the accepted aminonitrile intermediate to glycine (Woon, 2002; Danger et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of aminoacetonitrile to glycine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate minerals, montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"moist to aqueous setting; nitrile hydrolysis is the kinetic bottleneck\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise nitrile hydration and hydrolysis convert the aminonitrile into the amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis as the kinetic bottleneck of the Strecker route, strongly accelerated by water-mediated proton relays. This is one of the most literature-secure glycine syntheses and is kept as a principal route (Woon, 2002; Elsila et al., 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanosulfidic photoredox formation of aminoacetonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"308K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"sulfide minerals, phosphate buffer/catalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation; H2S present; neutral pH; cyanosulfidic systems chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photoredox cycling in cyanide/sulfide/phosphate networks selectively enriches aminonitriles from simple feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report specifically states that cyanosulfidic chemistry gives aminoacetonitrile efficiently at 35 degrees C and neutral pH, with phosphate acting as buffer/catalyst and UV as a selective photochemical filter. This provides a second, literature-grounded route into the same aminonitrile hub (Patel et al., 2015; Xu et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine with ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS/NiS-type sulfide mineral surfaces approximated here by mackinawite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"CO-rich hydrothermal porous-rock setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reductive amination of alpha-keto acid precursor yields the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies reductive amination of glyoxylate as a key Iron-Sulfur-World route to glycine, with alpha-amino acids produced experimentally on metal sulfides at 100 degrees C and 1 bar CO. This is one of the best-supported hydrothermal terminal steps (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1998; W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal ferroan-brucite-mediated nitrate reduction coupled to glyoxylate amination\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ferroan brucite-like serpentinization mineral function represented alongside Fe0/magnetite hydrothermal reductants\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent to serpentinization setting; 6-week reaction windows; nitrate reduced to ammonia in situ\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated nitrate reduction supplies reactive ammonia equivalents that drive reductive amination of glyoxylate to glycine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep report highlights ferroan brucite formed during serpentinization as a breakthrough system mediating nitrate reduction to ammonia coupled with glyoxylate amination to glycine, including lower but significant yields from nitrate. Because the allowed hydrothermal mineral list omits ferroan brucite, Fe0/magnetite are included as hydrothermal serpentinization-associated agents while the reasoning preserves the reported mineral context (Menez et al., 2018; 2024 ferroan-brucite nitrate-system study summarized in the report).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of glyoxal from formaldehyde pool\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite, magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"carbonyl condensation/redox processing at vent mineral interfaces\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C1 carbonyl compounds undergo mineral-mediated coupling/redox processing to give C2 dicarbonyl species.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This connector is included to avoid the previously criticized unsupported direct formaldehyde-plus-CO2 to glyoxylate shortcut. C1-to-C2 carbonyl elaboration in hydrothermal mineral settings is plausible though less directly demonstrated for this exact step; thus it is marked as a necessary but more speculative bridge consistent with carbonyl chemistry in vent systems (Cody et al., 2000; Muchowska et al., 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"High-energy atmospheric Garakuta chemistry yielding complex glycine precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-320K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral collection and deposition surfaces after atmospheric synthesis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"proton-irradiation-derived atmospheric organics deposited into surface waters; hydrolyzable macromolecular glycine precursors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy irradiation of simple gases forms macromolecular complex glycine precursors that release glycine upon hydrolysis after deposition.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report states that proton irradiation of CO, N2, and H2O generates complex glycine precursors (CGP, Garakuta molecules), with glycine the major hydrolysis product. This route should not be recast as an HCN source; instead it is treated directly as a glycine-precursor reservoir, correcting the prior mistake (Kobayashi et al., 1995; Miyakawa et al., 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface