ences, and clear Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow. Major weaknesses are concentrated in several upstream hydrothermal carbonyl transformations, especially direct CO2-to-formaldehyde and formaldehyde-to-glyoxal/glyoxylate steps, which are more speculative than the literature-backed terminal glycine-forming reactions. There are also some chemistry/annotation issues: the methanimine formula is incorrect as listed, hydroxyacetamide is not isomeric with glycine despite having the same formula, CGP is represented as a discrete small molecule despite being macromolecular, and some surface/hydrothermal reactions should explicitly name their mineral agents to satisfy the network specification. The biochemical tail from glycine to glycylglycine and diketopiperazine is plausible and literature-supported, though not essential for target achievement. Overall, the network is viable and scientifically coherent, but would be strengthened by tightening species definitions and replacing speculative hydrothermal feedstock generation with better-documented sources.\",\n  \"approved\": true,\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.91,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.9\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_008": 0.9, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_010": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.91, "pathway_coherence": 0.95, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.96, "overall_confidence": 0.92, "feedback": "This is the strongest and most literature-aligned route. The methanimine-to-aminoacetonitrile-to-glycine sequence matches the canonical Strecker framework for glycine. The main caveat is that aminoacetonitrile hydrolysis is the kinetic bottleneck and should ideally be described with explicit aqueous assistance or prolonged hydrothermal/surface hydrolysis conditions.", "approved": true, "problematic_reactions": [], "suggestions": ["Specify water-assisted hydrolysis conditions for aminoacetonitrile in rxn_010", "Include explicit 