al_progression\": 0.87,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.94,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.91,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent hydrothermal route aligned with iron-sulfur world literature. Reductive amination of glyoxylate with ammonia to glycine is one of the most experimentally grounded hydrothermal pathways. This is a concise but valid pathway, assuming glyoxylate availability from connected upstream chemistry.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"State the specific mineral catalyst and gas regime more explicitly, such as FeS/NiS or ferroan brucite depending on the intended literature anchor.\",\n        \"Clarify whether CO, H2, or vent redox gradients supply reducing equivalents.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.93\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.9,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.94,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.9,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.95,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"Very strong literature-aligned pathway reflecting the recent ferroan-brucite nitrate reduction system. It directly addresses the ammonia availability problem and is especially valuable because it links nitrate reduction to in situ ammonia generation and glyoxylate amination. This is the best single-step target-achieving route in the network.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Ensure the mineral agent is explicitly ferroan brucite rather than a generic hydrothermal setting.\",\n        \"Include realistic yield caveats, since nitrate-fed systems are lower-yield than ammonia-fed analogues.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.91\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.85,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.89,\n    